#: ../hardware_introduction.rst:214
msgid "The Robot HAT features four sets of 3Pin ADC (Analog to Digital Converter) pins, each spaced 2.54mm apart. These pins operate at a 3.3V power supply. The ADC function, offering 12-bit precision, is facilitated by an onboard microcontroller. Detailed instructions for reading ADC values are provided in the :ref:`on_board_mcu` section."
msgstr ""

#: ../hardware_introduction.rst:218
msgid "Also, ADC channel A4 is connected to the battery through a voltage divider using resistors, which will be used to measure the battery voltage to estimate the approximate battery charge."
msgstr ""

#: ../hardware_introduction.rst:221
msgid "The voltage divider ratio is 20K/10K, so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../hardware_introduction.rst:223
msgid "A4 voltage (Va4) = value_A4 / 4095.0 * 3.3"
msgstr ""

#: ../hardware_introduction.rst:224
msgid "Battery voltage (Vbat) = Va4*3"
msgstr ""

#: ../hardware_introduction.rst:225
msgid "Battery voltage (Vbat) = value_A4 / 4095.0 * 3.3 * 3"
msgstr ""

#: ../hardware_introduction.rst:230
msgid "PWM"
msgstr ""

#: ../hardware_introduction.rst:234
msgid "Robot HAT has 4 sets of 3Pin PWM pins, each spaced 2.54mm apart, and the power supply is 5V. The method of using the PWM is described in detail in :ref:`on_board_mcu`."
msgstr ""

#: ../hardware_introduction.rst:237
msgid "PWM13 & 14 channels are used for motor drive."
msgstr ""

#: ../hardware_introduction.rst:242
msgid "I2C"
msgstr ""

#: ../hardware_introduction.rst:246
msgid "The Robot HAT has two I2C interfaces. One is the P2.54 4-pin interface, and the other is the SH1.0 4-pin interface, which is compatible with QWIIC and STEMMA QT. These I2C interfaces are connected to the Raspberry Pi's I2C interface via GPIO2 (SDA) and GPIO3 (SCL). The board also features an :ref:`on_board_mcu`, and the two signal lines have 10K pull-up resistors."
msgstr ""

